N+1 query problem: ~200 database queries per game cycle kills scalability.

Location: api/src/games.rs:887-1071 (save_tribute_items, save_area_items)

Current:
```rust
for item in &items_to_update {
    db.update::<Option<Item>>(&item_id).content(item.clone()).await?;  // ❌ Individual
    db.insert::<Vec<TributeItemEdge>>("owns").relation(...).await?;     // ❌ Individual
}
```

Impact:
- 24 tributes × 3 items × 2 queries = 144 queries
- 5 areas × 5 items × 2 queries = 50 queries
- Total: ~200 queries per cycle

Fix:
```rust
// Batch update items
if !items_to_update.is_empty() {
    db.query("UPDATE item SET * IN $items")
        .bind(("items", items_to_update))
        .await?;
}

// Batch insert relations
let edges: Vec<_> = items_to_update.iter()
    .map(|item| TributeItemEdge { /* ... */ })
    .collect();
db.insert::<Vec<TributeItemEdge>>("owns").relation(edges).await?;
```

Expected: 70% query reduction (200 → 60 per cycle)

Acceptance Criteria:
- Batch operations implemented for item updates
- Batch operations for relation edges
- Query count measured before/after
- Performance benchmarks added

8 unsafe HashMap access patterns can crash API server.

Location: api/src/games.rs:915, 924 (and 6 others)

Problem Pattern:
```rust
if !new_map.contains_key(id) || new_map.get(id).unwrap().quantity == 0 {
    // Double lookup - check then unwrap
}
```

Issue: If contains_key succeeds but get fails (race condition), server crashes.

Fix:
```rust
if let Some(item) = new_map.get(id) {
    if item.quantity == 0 {
        // ...
    }
} else {
    // Handle missing key
}
```

Tasks:
1. Find all HashMap .unwrap() calls in api/
2. Replace with if let Some or match patterns
3. Add proper error handling for missing keys
4. Add tests for edge cases

Acceptance Criteria:
- Zero .unwrap() on HashMap operations
- Proper error handling for all cases
- Tests verify missing key handling
- No panics under any input

**Context**: Tribute processing does O(n²) linear searches through areas and tributes.

**Current Behavior**:
- Lines 263-270: process_event_for_area() does linear search through areas
- Lines 273-279: Linear search through tributes per event
- Lines 614-617: Linear search per tribute to find their area
- O(n) lookups per tribute (5 areas × 24 tributes = 120 lookups)

**Issues**:
- O(n²) complexity for tribute processing
- Repeated lookups for same data
- 40-50% performance overhead

**Desired Behavior**:
```rust
struct CycleCache {
    area_by_name: HashMap<Area, usize>,  // Area -> index
    tributes_by_area: HashMap<Area, Vec<usize>>,  // Area -> tribute indices
}

fn build_cycle_cache(&self) -> CycleCache {
    let mut area_by_name = HashMap::with_capacity(self.areas.len());
    let mut tributes_by_area: HashMap<Area, Vec<usize>> = HashMap::new();

    for (i, area) in self.areas.iter().enumerate() {
        if let Some(area_enum) = &area.area {
            area_by_name.insert(area_enum.clone(), i);
        }
    }

    for (i, tribute) in self.tributes.iter().enumerate() {
        tributes_by_area.entry(tribute.area.clone())
            .or_insert_with(Vec::new)
            .push(i);
    }

    CycleCache { area_by_name, tributes_by_area }
}
```

**Benefits**:
- 40-50% faster tribute processing
- O(n) → O(1) lookups
- Cleaner code

**Locations**:
- game/src/games.rs:261-376 (process_event_for_area)
- game/src/games.rs:587-617 (run_tribute_cycle)

**Priority**: High - significant performance gain

All items break after 1 use - too harsh, no equipment strategy.

Current:
```rust
// All weapons created with quantity=1, break immediately
pub fn new_random_weapon() -> Item {
    Item {
        quantity: 1,  // Always breaks after one use
        // ...
    }
}
```

Problem: Every combat uses up weapon, no strategic depth

Proposed:
```rust
// Variable durability based on item type/quality
pub fn new_random_weapon(rng: &mut impl Rng) -> Item {
    let durability = match item_type {
        ItemType::Weapon => rng.random_range(2..=5),  // 2-5 uses
        ItemType::Shield => rng.random_range(3..=7),  // 3-7 uses
        ItemType::Tool => rng.random_range(5..=10),   // 5-10 uses
    };
    Item {
        quantity: durability,
        // ...
    }
}

// Optional: Wear-based degradation
pub struct Item {
    pub max_durability: u32,
    pub current_durability: u32,  // Renamed from quantity
}

impl Item {
    pub fn apply_wear(&mut self, amount: u32) -> bool {
        self.current_durability = self.current_durability.saturating_sub(amount);
        self.current_durability == 0  // Returns true if broken
    }
}
```

Features:
- Random durability at creation
- Gradual degradation (75% → 50% → 25% → broken messages)
- Repair mechanics possible in future
- Strategic choices (save legendary weapon vs use now)

Acceptance Criteria:
- Durability randomized at creation
- Items last multiple uses
- Wear-based degradation implemented
- Messages indicate item condition
- Tests verify durability mechanics

